Interview Questions
1) What are built-in packages in Java? Give examples.
-->Built-in packages in Java are predefined groups of related classes, interfaces, and sub-packages that are part of the Java 
    Application Programming Interface (API). They come pre-installed with the Java Development Kit (JDK) and provide
    ready-to-use components for common tasks like data handling, networking, and input/output.

    Examples:
      java.lang → core classes (String, Math, System)
      java.util → utilities (ArrayList, Scanner, HashMap)
      java.io → input/output classes (File, BufferedReader)
      java.sql → database connectivity
      java.net → networking



2) Explain the difference between java.lang and java.util packages.
-->
| Feature        | `java.lang`                  | `java.util`                       |
| -------------- | ---------------------------- | --------------------------------- |
| Purpose        | Core language classes        | Utility classes                   |
| Import         | Automatically imported       | Must be imported manually         |
| Common Classes | String, System, Math, Object | ArrayList, Scanner, HashMap, Date |
| Usage          | Basic operations             | Data structures & utilities       |

👉 Example:

// java.lang (no import needed)
String name = "Karthikeya";

// java.util (import required)
import java.util.ArrayList;
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();



3) Which built-in package is automatically imported in every Java program?
-->The java.lang package is automatically imported by default.

    👉 That’s why you can directly use:    
    String
    System
    Math
    Object
    without writing an import statement.
    

4) Can you use a class from a built-in package without import? Explain.
-->✅ Yes, but only in two cases:

1. If the class is in java.lang:
No import needed
String s = "Hello";  // java.lang.String

2. If you use fully qualified class name:
No import needed, but longer syntax

java.util.ArrayList<Integer> list = new java.util.ArrayList<>();

❌ Otherwise, you must import:

import java.util.ArrayList;
